{"id":14880717,"mediaExerciseId":"24be9f4b-818d-4358-a920-07b478bc3dee","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"1","chapterTitle":"Introduction To Corporate Finance","groupId":612257,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":17,"solutions":[{"id":5669628,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this question, we are asked to determine the following:\n\n1. Primary disadvantage of a corporation;\n\n2. Provide two (2) advantages of a corporation","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/22/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/d686d02d74fe3e1a6962eddec7a19352/lateximg_large.png","width":759},"regular":{"height":54,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/22/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/d686d02d74fe3e1a6962eddec7a19352/lateximg.png","width":379}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we proceed, let us briefly define what a corporation is.\n\nA **corporation** is a legal organization, commonly referred to as a legal entity created by following a procedure prescribed by law.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/17547a837521d484793ced13c201069f/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/17547a837521d484793ced13c201069f/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"1. The most significant and primary disadvantage of a Corporation is **double taxation**.\n\n**Double taxation** occurs when the corporation's earnings are taxed, and its shareholders are taxed again for its dividends received from the corporation. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/9198f22df194295ac64b8dcb442d4387/lateximg_large.png","width":1016},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/9198f22df194295ac64b8dcb442d4387/lateximg.png","width":509}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"2. Two of some of the advantages of a corporation are as follows;\n\n- **Limited liability**\n- **Unlimited life**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/11ee4510c89938f4377099079e0a95b9/lateximg_large.png","width":864},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/11ee4510c89938f4377099079e0a95b9/lateximg.png","width":431}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"**Limited liability**\nSince the corporation exists as a legal person or entity on its own, shareholders are protected from being liable for business-related debts and obligations.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/13/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/fa07869e0d10961d251ab507d4c79ab8/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/13/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/fa07869e0d10961d251ab507d4c79ab8/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"**Unlimited life**\nCorporation has a perpetual life primarily due to their ease of transferring ownership through selling shares of stocks. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/11/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/abe655e1e8e841cb128cdbb442183a34/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/11/d162e17a6307fef52c9147d16b218951/abe655e1e8e841cb128cdbb442183a34/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"1611ef07-a09d-4ea3-9773-061d792e45a4","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6},{"id":6374200,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we will look at the major disadvantages and benefits of the corporate form of organization.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Let us first explain what the **corporate form of organization** is. The corporation is the largest of the three types (sole proprietorship, partnership, and corporation) of business organizations. It is an artificial being that exists independently of its owners. During its existence, it has its rights, power, attributes, and properties that are expressly authorized by law.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's now discuss the major **disadvantages**. The first one is double taxation. Profits are taxed both federally and stately. Dividends are treated as income and taxed again when paid to shareholders. Furthermore, depending on the type of corporation, the various types of income and other taxes that must be paid can necessitate a large amount of paperwork. \n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"There are several **benefits** to forming a corporation, including limited personal liability, easy ownership transfer, business continuity, and improved access to capital. In a corporation, the owners are only liable for the amount of money invested through the purchase of shares. This means that if the company goes bankrupt and has no money left to repay its creditors and lenders, the money invested in the company by its shareholders (via the purchase of its shares) will be used to repay the creditors and lenders.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"756d5ab1-7b8d-497c-b1b0-f6c0b90fbf9f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880718,"exerciseName":"4","page":17,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"32878eae-fb41-4406-a11c-15a8470188ed","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-1-critical-thinking-questions-4-32878eae-fb41-4406-a11c-15a8470188ed"},{"id":14880719,"exerciseName":"5","page":17,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"e0905ed4-f721-4694-98c4-d6eeac8ef0bc","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-1-critical-thinking-questions-5-e0905ed4-f721-4694-98c4-d6eeac8ef0bc"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880716,"exerciseName":"2","page":17,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"38c1519c-a93f-4470-97f0-473cda0b967e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-1-critical-thinking-questions-2-38c1519c-a93f-4470-97f0-473cda0b967e"},{"id":14880715,"exerciseName":"1","page":17,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"175d757d-b23c-448e-a8e6-3a21ed904b2e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-1-critical-thinking-questions-1-175d757d-b23c-448e-a8e6-3a21ed904b2e"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-1-critical-thinking-questions-3-24be9f4b-818d-4358-a920-07b478bc3dee"}